In Week 4 of Trump\'92s second term, the pattern that had been emerging snapped into clearer view. Power was not only being gathered at the center; it was being rewired. The week\'92s events showed an executive willing to treat the machinery of government as a set of levers for personal and factional aims, and a network of private allies ready to pull with him. At the same time, courts, civil servants, and parts of civil society pushed back, sometimes successfully, often at real risk. The result was not a dramatic lurch but a tightening of the frame: a state more hollowed, more personalized, and more willing to bend law, memory, and citizenship to its purposes. That is the shape of the week.\
\
On the Democracy Clock, last week ended at 7:40 p.m. It was already early evening in institutional terms, with many safeguards weakened but not yet gone. This week the public time remains 7:40 p.m., yet the underlying measure crept forward by 0.3 minutes. The face of the clock does not move, but the gears inside do. That small internal shift reflects a dense cluster of structural changes: the expansion of DOGE\'92s reach across the civil service, the Justice Department\'92s open protection of a politically useful mayor, the coordinated purge of information and memory, and the normalization of chaos as a governing method. Against this, courts ordered funds released, archives searched, and health pages restored. Those rulings mattered. They kept the hands from jumping. But they did not reverse the deeper trend toward an executive that acts first and dares the rest of the system to catch up.\
\
The most consequential development of Week 4 was the systematic capture and downsizing of the federal state. The repurposing of the U.S. Digital Service into Elon Musk\'92s Department of Government Efficiency, or DOGE, moved from experiment to architecture. DOGE was given sweeping authority to review operations, cancel payments, suspend programs, and target employees across agencies. A new executive order on \'93workforce optimization\'94 placed DOGE operatives in charge of hiring and firing throughout the government, with a one\uc0\u8209 in\u8209 four replacement rule that guarantees shrinkage. This was not a single budget cut. It was a parallel chain of command, run through a private ally, that could reach into USAID, NASA, NIH, the Social Security Administration, and beyond. The effect was structural. It shifted real control over the size and shape of the state from statutes and career managers to a small, loyal circle.\
\
That new apparatus was not left idle. DOGE and the White House moved quickly to thin the ranks and erase capacity. Mass layoffs swept through the Department of Education, the Small Business Administration, the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, and the General Services Administration. Probationary employees across the government were ordered fired, a move that could touch hundreds of thousands of people. A \'93Fork in the Road\'94 buyout program offered pay through September to any federal worker who agreed to resign, and when unions sued, a federal judge ruled they lacked standing, clearing the way for up to 65,000 departures. The Federal Executive Institute, which had trained generations of senior civil servants, was abolished by executive order. These were not symbolic gestures. They were a coordinated hollowing of the neutral civil service, replacing professional continuity with fear, precarity, and political dependence. People who once expected to serve any administration now had to weigh each day against the risk of being targeted.\
\
At the same time, key oversight and ethics posts were stripped away or brought to heel. The director of the Office of Government Ethics was fired. The head of the Federal Election Commission and the Archivist of the United States were removed, weakening independent control over campaign rules and presidential records. Inspectors general who had been dismissed earlier in the term filed suit to challenge their ousters, arguing that brief emails citing \'93changing priorities\'94 could not lawfully erase statutory protections. The inspector general at USAID was fired a day after issuing a critical report on efforts to dismantle the agency. At the National Archives, top leadership was purged while the institution was responsible for investigating Trump\'92s own handling of classified documents. Taken together, these moves did not simply change personnel. They signaled that offices built to watch the executive would be tolerated only if they served it. Oversight itself was being put on probation.\
\
The Justice Department, which in a healthy system stands between political power and the law, moved further into the role of shield and sword for the regime. The most vivid example came in the corruption case against New York City Mayor Eric Adams. Federal prosecutors had indicted Adams on charges including bribery and illegal foreign campaign contributions. Then DOJ leadership in Washington ordered the case dropped, arguing that the prosecution interfered with Adams\'92s usefulness on immigration enforcement. At least six prosecutors, including the acting U.S. attorney, resigned rather than sign their names to the dismissal. The same pattern appeared in the department\'92s decision to halt investigations into Elon Musk\'92s companies, including Tesla and SpaceX, and in the abolition of the FBI\'92s Foreign Influence Task Force and a Justice Department unit targeting Russian oligarchs. Law enforcement resources were being pulled away from probing powerful allies and foreign interference, and redirected toward sanctuary cities and state laws that eased life for undocumented residents. Law was being steered, not followed.\
\
At the top of the legal system, the president used his own powers to similar effect. An executive order paused enforcement of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, the main U.S. law against bribing foreign officials. The move was framed as a way to \'93promote American competitiveness,\'94 but in practice it told corporations that paying off foreign power brokers would no longer draw federal charges. On the same day, Trump pardoned former Illinois governor Rod Blagojevich, convicted of trying to sell a U.S. Senate seat. The message was plain. Corruption by those in the political class could be forgiven by personal favor, while the tools meant to deter it abroad were set aside. Law was being converted from a limit on power into a flexible instrument of advantage. It was a weapon and a shield, depending on who stood where.\
\
Courts did not accept this passively. Federal judges blocked the administration from placing thousands of USAID employees on leave, from shutting down the agency outright, and from giving DOGE access to the Treasury Department\'92s central payment systems. They ordered the destruction of any Treasury data already copied by Musk\'92s team. They enjoined the NIH from imposing a 15 percent cap on indirect research costs, and later forced the administration to admit that its funding freeze had been illegal and to resume issuing grants. They halted an executive order ending birthright citizenship and another that sought to strip federal funding from hospitals and clinics providing gender\uc0\u8209 affirming care to transgender youth. They ordered health agencies to restore deleted web pages on HIV testing and contraception, and compelled the FBI to search its records in response to a Freedom of Information Act request about Trump\'92s classified documents. In each case, the judiciary asserted that even a determined executive must obey law and process. The courts were still willing to say no.\
\
Yet the cost of that resistance rose. Elon Musk amplified a post that exposed personal information about a judge\'92s daughter, inviting harassment of a jurist whose rulings had crossed his interests. Representative Eli Crane drafted articles of impeachment against Judge Paul Engelmayer for blocking DOGE\'92s access to Treasury systems, framing judicial oversight as partisan overreach. USAID employees were turned away from their headquarters even after a court ordered their return, and Customs and Border Protection officials toured the building as if preparing to take it over. The administration maintained an NIH funding freeze for weeks in defiance of two injunctions, only backing down when internal memos were exposed. These acts of defiance and intimidation did not yet break the courts, but they tested how far judges would go to enforce their orders against an executive willing to ignore them. The line between a contested ruling and an empty one grew thinner.\
\
Information and memory became another front in this struggle. On his first day back in office, Trump signed orders requiring health agencies to scrub terms related to race, gender, sexual orientation, disability, and other diversity topics from their websites and grant proposals. HIV data vanished. References to transgender and intersex people were erased from LGBTQI acronyms. Across at least 8,000 federal web pages, DEI, LGBTQ+ health, and climate content was removed or rewritten. At the National Security Agency, an internal \'93Big Delete\'94 targeted 27 banned words, including \'93privilege,\'94 \'93bias,\'94 and \'93inclusion,\'94 sweeping up mission\uc0\u8209 related material in a chaotic purge managed in part by interns. NASA\'92s diversity offices were closed, and staff were told to strip DEI language from public sites, even as employees worried about the safety of missions that depend on open reporting of problems. What the public could see of its own government was being narrowed by design.\
\
The same impulse reached into education and commemoration. Pentagon schools serving military families suspended access to library books for a \'93compliance review\'94 focused on gender and equity topics, pulling titles from shelves and restricting them to staff. The National Park Service removed all references to transgender people from the Stonewall National Monument website, erasing the role of trans women of color in the 1969 uprising that the monument exists to honor. At the Kennedy Center, Trump fired the board and declared himself chair, asserting personal control over a national cultural institution. These were not isolated edits. They were part of a broader effort to curate what the public may see about who counts in American history and who belongs in its present. Memory itself was being managed from above.\
\
Press freedom came under direct pressure as well. The White House barred two Associated Press reporters from events after the AP refused to adopt the administration\'92s preferred term \'93Gulf of America\'94 for the Gulf of Mexico. Days later, it announced an indefinite ban on AP journalists from the Oval Office and Air Force One, accusing the outlet of misinformation while insisting that access to those spaces was a privilege. The AP retained credentials for the White House complex, but its ability to question the president in the most visible settings was cut off. At the same time, Elon Musk\'92s DOGE website published classified information about the National Reconnaissance Office\'92s budgets and personnel, blurring the line between transparency and reckless exposure of intelligence capabilities. Social media platform X agreed to pay Trump $10 million to settle his lawsuit over his post\'96January 6 ban, following a larger settlement from Meta, signaling the financial risks of moderating powerful figures. The net effect was to tilt the information environment toward those aligned with the regime and to warn independent outlets that defiance carried costs. Access and money both leaned in one direction.\
\
Immigration and citizenship policy showed how law and force could be used to stratify belonging. Trump issued an executive order prioritizing asylum for Afrikaners from South Africa, citing race\uc0\u8209 based discrimination, even as South African officials and Afrikaner groups themselves denied any such persecution. On his first day in office he cut funding to a Colorado nonprofit that provided free legal services to undocumented immigrants, in a state already short on representation. ICE raids in Denver and Aurora, conducted by heavily armed teams and sometimes accompanied by a Fox News crew, arrested 30 people, only one of whom was a confirmed gang member. ICE arrested more than 8,200 people nationwide in late January, but released only aggregate numbers without details on where or whom they had detained. Border Czar Tom Homan complained that deportations were too slow and sanctuary cities too obstructive, promising more aggressive actions, including against non\u8209 criminals. The message was that presence itself, not conduct, could mark someone as a target.\
\
Local and state actors were drawn into this regime. New York City Mayor Eric Adams announced plans to reopen an ICE office at Rikers Island, and then did so, reversing sanctuary policies that had kept immigration enforcement off city jail grounds. In Colorado, Representative Lauren Boebert and others pressured the governor to repeal immigrant protections, even as he endorsed the core of Trump\'92s deportation plan. The Justice Department sued New York over its \'93green light\'94 law allowing undocumented residents to obtain driver\'92s licenses, and filed a separate suit against the state\'92s broader immigration policies. The Denver public school system sued to block ICE access to schools, arguing that the presence of agents on campus forced them to divert resources and drove students away. In Fremont, California, the city council passed one of the strictest anti\uc0\u8209 camping ordinances in the state, criminalizing not only sleeping on public land but also \'93aiding and abetting\'94 homeless encampments. These measures used law and security forces to mark certain people\'97immigrants, the unhoused, transgender youth\'97as less entitled to safety and support. Citizenship was being graded in practice, if not yet in statute.\
\
The same logic extended beyond U.S. borders. Trump announced a plan to \'93take over Gaza,\'94 remove all Palestinians from the strip, and resettle them in neighboring countries, framing the territory as a future real estate asset. He proposed canceling a ceasefire if hostages were not released by a fixed deadline, saying \'93all hell\'94 should break loose. In parallel, he and his allies floated demands that Ukraine cede rights to vast mineral reserves in exchange for continued U.S. support, with reports of a proposal granting the United States 50 percent of Ukraine\'92s future mineral wealth. The Secretary of Defense told European allies that the U.S. would no longer prioritize European security and would withdraw troops over time, urging Europe to take the lead in supporting Ukraine. Vice President JD Vance met with the leader of Germany\'92s far\uc0\u8209 right AfD party at the Munich Security Conference, breaking a long\u8209 standing taboo in German politics, and defended Elon Musk\'92s support for far\u8209 right candidates while downplaying Russian election interference. These moves repositioned U.S. power away from liberal\u8209 democratic norms and toward a more openly transactional, illiberal posture. Foreign policy, too, was being personalized and monetized.\
