Appointments during the week reinforced the pattern of loyalty and ideology over competence. Russell Vought, a chief architect of plans to expand presidential power and demoralize the civil service, was confirmed as director of the Office of Management and Budget. Robert F. Kennedy Jr., a prominent vaccine skeptic, was confirmed as Secretary of Health and Human Services, placing federal health agencies under the leadership of someone who has long attacked their core work. Tulsi Gabbard, whose past statements have been sympathetic to foreign adversaries, was confirmed as Director of National Intelligence, despite bipartisan concerns about her qualifications. Elon Musk appointed a 19\uc0\u8209 year\u8209 old internet personality as a senior adviser to the State Department. Trump fired the Kennedy Center board and declared himself its chair. Mark Burnett, the television producer behind \'93The Apprentice,\'94 was named special envoy to the United Kingdom. These choices did not simply fill vacancies. They seeded key posts with figures whose main credential was alignment with the president\'92s worldview or personal history, further weakening the expectation that public office is a trust held for the whole polity. The state\'92s upper floors were being staffed like a show.\
\
Amid this, there were pockets of resilience and adaptation. Federal judges repeatedly enforced limits on executive power, as when they ordered the release of frozen funds to farmers and foreign aid recipients, blocked the shutdown of USAID, and reinstated the head of the Office of Special Counsel. NIH, after weeks of defiance, issued an internal memo acknowledging that its funding freeze had violated court orders and instructing staff to resume grants under existing rules. The American Bar Association issued a formal statement condemning the administration\'92s violations of the rule of law. Five former Treasury secretaries warned in a joint op\uc0\u8209 ed that DOGE\'92s fiscal maneuvers and Trump\'92s talk of not honoring debt obligations threatened the constitutional framework for federal spending. State and local actors, from Pennsylvania\'92s governor suing to compel the release of $3 billion in withheld funds to Denver\'92s school district challenging ICE access, used the courts to defend their own authority and their residents\'92 rights. These were not small acts. They showed that some levers still worked.\
\
Civil society, too, remained active. Tens of millions of calls jammed congressional phone lines as constituents demanded that their representatives oppose Trump and Musk\'92s efforts to dismantle agencies and access private data. Over 300,000 people marched in Munich against the far\uc0\u8209 right AfD and its anti\u8209 immigrant agenda. North Carolina activists organized a \'93Disenfranchised Disco\'94 to draw attention to 60,000 residents barred from voting, and a new progressive caucus in the state legislature introduced bills to limit immigration enforcement in sensitive locations like schools and hospitals. The North Carolina Democratic Party planned a rally at the state capitol to oppose bills seen as undermining democracy. These actions did not stop the executive orders or the firings. But they showed that the public sphere was not yet silent, and that some officials still responded to pressure from below. The streets and phone lines remained part of the story.\
\
Looking ahead from Week 4, several lines of conflict were already in motion. Lawsuits challenging DOGE\'92s legality, its access to Treasury systems, and its role in shutting down agencies were pending in multiple courts. Judges had issued temporary restraining orders on the NIH cuts, the USAID shutdown, the birthright citizenship order, and the transgender health\uc0\u8209 care ban, with further hearings scheduled. The National Treasury Employees Union\'92s suit over the attempted closure of the CFPB would test whether the executive could dismantle a congressionally created agency by starving it of funds. Pennsylvania\'92s case over withheld federal money, and similar suits by other states, would clarify how far a president could go in weaponizing appropriations against disfavored regions. Abroad, planned negotiations between Trump and Vladimir Putin over Ukraine, and the administration\'92s declared intention to \'93own\'94 Gaza, would reveal how much U.S. allies were willing to accept in the way of territorial concessions and resource deals. The next moves would show whether these tests hardened into precedent.\
\
By the end of the week, the Democracy Clock still read 7:40 p.m., but the meaning of that hour had deepened. The formal structures of democracy remained: elections scheduled, courts sitting, legislatures meeting, newspapers publishing. Yet inside those structures, the balance of power shifted further toward an executive that treated law as a tool, the civil service as a disposable workforce, and public memory as something to be edited for advantage. Chaos\'97funding freezes announced and rescinded, agencies gutted and then partially restored, foreign policy lines drawn and redrawn\'97was not an accident but a method. It fragmented attention, overwhelmed oversight, and made it harder for any single institution to mount a sustained defense. The system still stood, but it was being shaken from within.\
\
Week 4 matters in the larger arc of the term because it shows how quickly a determined leadership can move from rhetoric to structure. DOGE\'92s authority, the mass firings, the politicized appointments, the information purges, and the selective enforcement of law all advanced together. Courts, states, and citizens pushed back, and in some cases they won. Those victories kept the clock from jumping forward on its face. But the underlying movement of 0.3 minutes reminds us that resistance, while real, is now working against a government that has begun to rewire itself. The official time at the close of Week 4 remains 7:40 p.m. The daylight of a fully functioning democracy is still visible in the distance, but the shadows are longer, and the path back grows steeper with each passing week.\
